# Nonliteral Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p4f8qe"
idioms
mean
exactly
what words
say
```

or:

```text id="u1f5qe"
figurative language
=
incorrect language
```

Some may:

```text id="c7f2qe"
interpret
phrases
literally
```

without understanding:

```text id="k9f6qe"
authors
sometimes
mean
more than
literal words
```

Example:

phrase:

```text id="n2f4qe"
break the ice
```

students may say:

```text id="t8f1qe"
crack frozen water
```

instead of recognizing:

```text id="q5f9qe"
start conversation
or reduce tension
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="v3f7qe"
figurative reasoning
```

For Grade 4:

focus includes:

Figurative Language:

* simile
* metaphor
* personification
* hyperbole
* imagery

Idioms:

* nonliteral phrases
* meaning from context
* common expressions
* interpretation

Important idea:

```text id="a7f3qe"
literal
=
exact meaning

figurative
=
implied meaning
```

